{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Every time you check the weather app before picking clothes, you’re using probability. A 40% rain forecast nudges you toward packing an umbrella, even if the sky looks fine right now.",
      "title": "Checking the Weather"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you’re choosing a checkout line at the grocery store, you estimate which line will move faster based on how many items people have and how quickly the cashier works.",
      "title": "Choosing a Checkout Line"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sports fans use probability without noticing it. When your team is down by a few points with seconds left, you instantly sense the chance of a comeback based on how often you’ve seen it happen.",
      "title": "Watching Sports"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scrolling through social media, you might guess the chances your post gets likes based on what time you usually get the most engagement.",
      "title": "Posting on Social Media"
    },
    {
      "text": "When deciding whether to order delivery or cook at home, you weigh the odds of the food arriving late or cold against the effort of cooking.",
      "title": "Dinner Decisions"
    },
    {
      "text": "At work, estimating the chance a project finishes on time helps you set realistic deadlines and avoid last‑minute chaos.",
      "title": "Project Deadlines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Driving through traffic, you choose lanes and routes based on the probability they’ll move faster, using past experience as your guide.",
      "title": "Navigating Traffic"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you see a sale sign like “70% off select items,” you mentally gauge the odds that the thing you actually want is part of the discount.",
      "title": "Shopping Sales"
    },
    {
      "text": "Planning a trip, you might pick travel dates by looking at the likelihood of good weather or crowded attractions.",
      "title": "Planning a Trip"
    },
    {
      "text": "Even when playing board games or cards, you sense the chance of drawing a winning piece based on what’s already been played.",
      "title": "Game Night Choices"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Ever try to buy strawberries when they’re suddenly everywhere in summer? Prices slide because farms are harvesting lots at once, and stores are eager to move them quickly.",
      "title": "Summer Fruit Prices"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a big concert comes to town, tickets vanish fast. As more fans scramble to buy, sellers feel confident raising prices, knowing demand is sky‑high.",
      "title": "Concert Ticket Rush"
    },
    {
      "text": "After a storm, hardware stores run low on generators. With so many people needing them at the same time, shelves empty and prices creep upward.",
      "title": "Post‑Storm Shortages"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a new video game console releases, people camp outside stores. Limited units plus excited fans push prices up, even in resale markets.",
      "title": "Hot Tech Releases"
    },
    {
      "text": "During back‑to‑school season, stores order more notebooks and backpacks because they know families will be buying. High demand makes retailers stock up heavily.",
      "title": "Seasonal Shopping Waves"
    },
    {
      "text": "Farmers deal with it daily: a bumper crop means more produce and lower selling prices, while a weak harvest tightens supply and raises what buyers pay.",
      "title": "Life on the Farm"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rideshare apps often surge in price during rush hour. Lots of riders, not enough drivers — the app bumps prices to balance the crowd.",
      "title": "Rush‑Hour Ride Prices"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Standing between two mirrors and seeing endless reflections is a real-life peek at recursion — each reflection holds a smaller version of the same scene, repeating deeper and deeper.",
      "title": "Mirror Reflections"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you sort a messy room by clearing one small corner at a time, then repeating the same pattern in the next corner, you're unknowingly following a recursive rhythm.",
      "title": "Tidying One Spot at a Time"
    },
    {
      "text": "Looking at a fern, you’ll notice each leaf looks like a tiny fern of its own. Nature repeats shapes at different scales, almost like it’s calling the same pattern again and again.",
      "title": "Ferns and Repeating Shapes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Zooming in on a coastline on a map — then zooming again — you keep seeing the same jagged outline. It’s a real-world example of structures repeating at smaller scales.",
      "title": "Endless Coastline Zoom"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you forward a message in a group chat and it keeps getting forwarded again, the conversation thread starts to form a branching, self-repeating structure.",
      "title": "Chain-Forwarded Messages"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you’ve ever played a game where each boss has mini-versions of itself or repeats the same attack pattern in smaller bursts, you’ve met recursion disguised as gameplay design.",
      "title": "Video Game Mini-Boss Patterns"
    },
    {
      "text": "Artists who draw a picture inside the same picture — like a hand drawing a hand — use recursive imagery to create that mind-bending loop feeling.",
      "title": "Art That Contains Itself"
    },
    {
      "text": "When organizing a family tree, each person branches into parents, grandparents, and so on. The same structure repeats downward through every generation.",
      "title": "Family Tree Branching"
    },
    {
      "text": "Breaking a big work task into smaller chunks, then breaking each chunk again until you're down to something doable, mirrors the recursive way problems shrink step by step.",
      "title": "Shrinking Work Tasks"
    },
    {
      "text": "A nesting-doll toy repeats the same design as you open doll after doll. Each smaller version feels like the same idea wrapped inside itself.",
      "title": "Nesting Dolls"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Sabe quando você entra no supermercado só para comprar pão e sai com promoções que nem precisava? Aqueles rótulos chamativos e “leve 2, pague 1” ativam vieses que fazem parecer vantajoso algo que talvez nem estivesse na sua lista.",
      "title": "O Mercado Te Puxando"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando você decide em qual restaurante confiar olhando só as avaliações positivas, é fácil ignorar críticas relevantes. Você acaba montando uma imagem com base apenas no que encaixa no que queria acreditar desde o início.",
      "title": "Escolhendo Onde Comer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Num debate político, é comum dar mais atenção aos comentários que reforçam o lado que você já apoia. O feed das redes sociais vira um espelho das suas crenças, fazendo parecer que “todo mundo concorda” com você.",
      "title": "Rolando o Feed Político"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando alguém que você gosta dá um pequeno deslize, você encontra mil desculpas. Mas se for alguém com quem já tem implicância, o mesmo erro parece enorme. Seu cérebro ajusta o peso dos fatos conforme o afeto.",
      "title": "Julgar Quem Você Gosta"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ao procurar produtos online, a etiqueta “mais vendido” ou “escolha da loja” faz parecer que aquela é a opção certa. Mesmo sem perceber, você segue a trilha da maioria como se isso garantisse qualidade.",
      "title": "O Rótulo de “Mais Vendido”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Num jogo de futebol, torcedores juram que o árbitro “roubou” para o outro time. A mesma jogada é vista como falta ou lance normal dependendo da camisa que você defende.",
      "title": "Torcida e Arbitragem"
    },
    {
      "text": "Na fila do banco ou no trânsito, quando alguém te fecha, você pensa “que pessoa horrível”. Mas se você faz o mesmo por distração, vira “foi só um momento ruim”. Mudamos o julgamento conforme o lado da história.",
      "title": "A Trapaça do Julgamento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando aprende um hobby novo — cozinhar, tocar violão, fotografar — é comum comparar seu começo ao auge de outras pessoas. Seu cérebro esquece que elas também começaram pequenas e cria uma sensação de incapacidade.",
      "title": "Se Comparando nos Hobbies"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cuando un medicamento deja de funcionarte porque las bacterias ya “no le tienen miedo”, estás viendo en vivo cómo las que resistieron la primera dosis fueron las que se multiplicaron.",
      "title": "Antibioticos que dejan de servir"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si notas que los mosquitos de tu zona ya casi no les afectan ciertos repelentes, es porque los que aguantaron esos químicos fueron los que siguieron reproduciéndose.",
      "title": "Mosquitos que resisten repelentes"
    },
    {
      "text": "En los parques, las palomas más audaces se acercan a la gente y consiguen más comida. Con el tiempo, ese comportamiento atrevido se vuelve más común en la población.",
      "title": "Palomas urbanas más atrevidas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los agricultores ven cómo ciertas plagas empiezan a sobrevivir a los pesticidas de siempre. Las que aguantan esos productos son las que reconstruyen la población.",
      "title": "Plagas que burlan pesticidas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando crías perros o gatos, algunas líneas familiares muestran rasgos muy marcados, como energía, tamaño o carácter. Con cada camada, ciertos rasgos se vuelven más frecuentes.",
      "title": "Rasgos que se fijan en mascotas"
    },
    {
      "text": "En acuarios caseros, algunos peces toleran mejor el agua más cálida o fría. Esos sobreviven cuando algo falla en el termostato, cambiando lentamente la mezcla de rasgos del grupo.",
      "title": "Peces que toleran cambios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los guardaparques notan que los venados más cautelosos evitan zonas peligrosas y dejan más crías. En unos años, la población completa parece más “desconfiada”.",
      "title": "Venados más cautelosos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Incluso en tu jardín, las malezas que logran crecer pese a que las arrancas son las que esparcen sus semillas. Cada temporada parece que son más difíciles de eliminar.",
      "title": "Malezas que se vuelven tenaces"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When your phone suggests the next word as you type, it’s drawing on patterns learned from huge samples of language. It feels like your keyboard is reading your mind because it’s constantly predicting what you’ll probably say next.",
      "title": "Your Phone’s Typing Suggestions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scroll through TikTok or Instagram and notice how your feed shifts. The apps study what you linger on and keep serving you more of that style. It’s like a personal DJ figuring out your vibe from your reactions.",
      "title": "Your Personalized Social Feeds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ask your smart speaker to play a song, and it understands your voice enough to act instantly. It gets better at recognizing you the more you talk to it, almost like it’s tuning itself to your speech quirks.",
      "title": "Smart Speakers Catching Your Voice"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you take a photo and your camera automatically sharpens faces or brightens the sky, it’s using learned patterns to guess what will make the picture look best. It’s like having a tiny photo editor inside your phone.",
      "title": "Your Camera’s Auto-Magic Touch"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a shopping site shows “You might also like,” it’s comparing your picks with patterns from thousands of shoppers. It’s the online version of a store clerk who remembers what people with similar tastes tend to buy next.",
      "title": "Shopping Recommendations"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your email quietly sorts suspicious messages into spam. It compares wording, structure, and behavior to messages people have flagged before. You barely notice it, but it’s working overtime to keep your inbox clean.",
      "title": "Spam Filters Guarding Your Inbox"
    },
    {
      "text": "When GPS apps warn you about traffic ahead or reroute you, they’re spotting patterns in tons of location data. It’s like having a navigator who’s checked every road a million times.",
      "title": "Traffic Predictions While Driving"
    },
    {
      "text": "Streaming apps notice what you watch, when you stop, and what you rewatch. Then they suggest shows that match your habits. It’s like having a friend who always knows what you’re in the mood for.",
      "title": "What to Watch Next"
    },
    {
      "text": "Banks quietly compare your spending habits to typical patterns. If something looks off, they flag it. It’s similar to a friend saying, “That doesn’t seem like you,” but way faster.",
      "title": "Fraud Detection at the Bank"
    },
    {
      "text": "Some games adjust difficulty based on how you play. Struggling? They ease up. Crushing it? They ramp up the challenge. It’s like the game is learning your style and trying to keep things fun.",
      "title": "Adaptive Difficulty in Games"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When your savings account quietly grows each month, it isn’t just the deposit doing the work. Last month’s interest is now earning its own tiny bit of interest, turning your balance into a snowball rolling downhill.",
      "title": "Your Savings Snowball"
    },
    {
      "text": "Swipe a credit card and let the balance linger, and you’ll see compounding in reverse. Interest added this month becomes part of the balance that gets charged interest next month, making small slips turn into stubborn debt.",
      "title": "Credit Card Creep"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you invest early in a retirement account, the money you put in during your 20s quietly works for you for decades. Even small contributions grow into something surprising because each year’s gains help produce next year’s gains.",
      "title": "Retirement Accounts Growing Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a streamer or influencer grows followers, each new follower can bring another. That growth builds on itself—much like money compounding—turning a modest audience into a booming one.",
      "title": "Followers Building Momentum"
    },
    {
      "text": "Watering a plant regularly helps it grow a bit each week, but as it gets bigger, it produces more leaves and branches, which then grow even more. Its growth feels faster later on, just like compounding over time.",
      "title": "A Plant That Grows Faster Later"
    },
    {
      "text": "Learning a new skill works the same way. Each bit of progress makes the next bit easier—your practice builds on previous practice, so improvement speeds up instead of staying flat.",
      "title": "Skill Growth That Builds on Itself"
    },
    {
      "text": "Businesses feel compounding when reinvesting profits. A small store that expands inventory or advertising using last year’s profits can generate even more profit next year, creating a cycle of accelerating growth.",
      "title": "Businesses Reinventing Profits"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Quando você abre a janela de manhã e sente o ar fresco entrando, está respirando o resultado direto da fotossíntese. Árvores e plantas ao redor renovam o oxigênio que preenche sua casa sem que você perceba.",
      "title": "O ar da sua manhã"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquela salada colorida no almoço só existe porque cada folha já transformou luz em energia armazenada. Cada garfada é energia solar que viajou pelas plantas até você.",
      "title": "No seu prato de comida"
    },
    {
      "text": "Durante uma caminhada no parque, a sombra gostosa sob uma árvore é só a ponta do iceberg: ela cresce, floresce e se mantém viva graças à fotossíntese que rola ali o dia inteiro.",
      "title": "Passeando no parque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando você dirige por uma estrada cercada por plantações, está vendo enormes “fábricas de energia solar natural”. Lavouras dependem totalmente da fotossíntese para produzir grãos, frutas e fibras.",
      "title": "Viajando por áreas rurais"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquela madeira do móvel ou o papel do seu caderno vieram de árvores que guardaram anos de energia capturada da luz. Mesmo transformados, os produtos carregam a história da fotossíntese.",
      "title": "Nos objetos do dia a dia"
    },
    {
      "text": "Nos filmes e jogos que mostram florestas exuberantes ou mundos alienígenas cheios de plantas estranhas, a ideia de organismos captando luz para viver sempre está por trás dessas paisagens vibrantes.",
      "title": "Cenários da cultura pop"
    },
    {
      "text": "Se você cultiva suculentas ou temperos na janela, já viu como elas se inclinam para onde a luz bate mais. É a fotossíntese guiando cada esticadinha em direção ao sol.",
      "title": "No seu cantinho de plantas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando cientistas falam sobre mudanças climáticas, muitas vezes mencionam florestas e algas como “sumidouros de carbono”. Elas retiram CO2 do ar justamente graças à fotossíntese.",
      "title": "Nas conversas sobre clima"
    },
    {
      "text": "Nos oceanos, microalgas invisíveis fazem uma grande parte do oxigênio do planeta. Quem mergulha ou simplesmente olha o mar está diante de um dos maiores centros de fotossíntese da Terra.",
      "title": "No fundo do mar"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cada vez que mandas un mensaje en una app de chat, viaja como un secreto sellado. Tú escribes algo normal, pero en el camino se vuelve un mensaje indescifrable para cualquiera que intente fisgonear.",
      "title": "Mensajes que viajan blindados"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando haces una compra en línea, tu tarjeta no viaja “tal cual”. Es como si la tienda recibiera una versión en clave, imposible de leer para quien intercepte el camino.",
      "title": "Pagos en línea sin miedo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ese candadito del Wi‑Fi de tu casa no es adorno. Mantiene tus conversaciones, fotos y búsquedas envueltas en una burbuja que los vecinos o intrusos no pueden descifrar.",
      "title": "Tu Wi‑Fi como burbuja privada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando subes fotos a la nube, no se guardan “abiertas”. Se almacenan como si estuvieran dentro de una caja fuerte digital, cerrada incluso para la propia empresa que ofrece el servicio.",
      "title": "Tus recuerdos guardados en clave"
    },
    {
      "text": "Al desbloquear tu teléfono con huella o rostro, el dispositivo abre un cofre donde tus apps y datos estaban encriptados. Sin tu señal, seguirían siendo un rompecabezas sin piezas.",
      "title": "Tu celular como cofre digital"
    },
    {
      "text": "En videollamadas, tu voz y tu imagen se rompen en fragmentos incomprensibles mientras viajan. Solo se reconstruyen en la pantalla de quien debe recibirlos.",
      "title": "Videollamadas protegidas en tránsito"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si usas banca digital, el saldo, movimientos y confirmaciones viajan ocultos. Es como si cada operación se escribiera con tinta invisible hasta llegar al banco.",
      "title": "Movimientos bancarios invisibles"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando instalas una app, tus datos de inicio de sesión se guardan encriptados. Incluso si alguien revisara el interior de la app, solo vería garabatos sin sentido.",
      "title": "Tus cuentas guardadas en secreto"
    },
    {
      "text": "Al conectar un dispositivo Bluetooth, como audífonos, la música no viaja “abierta”. Va disfrazada, para que nadie pueda interceptarla o reproducirla sin permiso.",
      "title": "Sonido que viaja disfrazado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los servicios de salud digital ocultan resultados, citas y diagnósticos en capas de cifrado. Es como si tus datos médicos llevaran bata y mascarilla para que nadie los reconozca.",
      "title": "Salud digital con identidad oculta"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Think about hitting snooze. The groggier you feel, the more you delay getting up. Each tap makes waking harder, nudging you into a loop that reinforces staying in bed.",
      "title": "Morning Snooze Cycle"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you post something online and people like it, you tend to post more of the same. More posts bring more engagement, and the cycle keeps reinforcing your behavior.",
      "title": "Social Media Momentum"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plants in a garden can create stabilizing loops. As they grow, they shade the soil, keeping it cooler and moist, helping them stay healthy and continue growing steadily.",
      "title": "Garden Self-Stabilizing"
    },
    {
      "text": "At work, if your team communicates clearly, small problems get addressed quickly, preventing bigger issues. Calm communication feeds back into more calm communication.",
      "title": "Team Communication Flow"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a crowd starts cheering at a game, energy builds. One section gets louder, boosting nearby sections. Before long, the whole stadium is roaring.",
      "title": "Stadium Energy Build-Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you snack when stressed, the temporary comfort can make you rely on snacking more often. The short-term relief loops back, reinforcing the habit.",
      "title": "Stress-Snacking Habit Loop"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your fitness tracker buzzing when you're inactive nudges you to move. That small action prevents long stretches of sitting, keeping your daily activity more balanced.",
      "title": "Activity Tracker Nudges"
    },
    {
      "text": "In neighborhoods, well-kept yards encourage others to tidy up too. Each house that improves pushes the area to keep rising in appearance and pride.",
      "title": "Neighborhood Ripple Effect"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When you hit snooze, you’re not just choosing more sleep — you’re giving up a calmer morning, a real breakfast, or a less rushed commute. That tiny tap hides a trade-off your day still feels.",
      "title": "The Morning Snooze Button"
    },
    {
      "text": "Picking a $6 latte feels simple, but it quietly trades away money you could put toward lunch, a savings goal, or that weekend plan. Your cup tastes great, but it comes with a silent “instead of.”",
      "title": "Your Daily Coffee Run"
    },
    {
      "text": "Choosing to answer emails during a meeting might seem productive, but it costs you the chance to catch key info or contribute at the right moment. Multitasking always has a hidden price tag.",
      "title": "Office Multitasking Moments"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scrolling TikTok for “just five minutes” steals time from finishing a chore, texting a friend back, or practicing a hobby. Apps feel free, but your attention is the currency they spend.",
      "title": "Endless Social Media Scrolls"
    },
    {
      "text": "Deciding to binge a new show on Friday means skipping that dinner invite or losing time for your weekend reset. Even relaxation has a ‘what else could I have done?’ lingering beneath it.",
      "title": "Choosing a Friday Night Plan"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you choose to play a video game for an hour, you’re also choosing not to level up your guitar skills or work on your cosplay project. Fun has trade-offs too — just more enjoyable ones.",
      "title": "Hobby Time Trade-Offs"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you stay in a job you’ve outgrown, you keep your stability but trade away the chance to learn new skills or try a different role. Even non-decisions carry hidden costs.",
      "title": "Staying in a Comfortable Job"
    },
    {
      "text": "Signing up for a gym membership you rarely use isn’t just money spent — it’s money you could’ve put toward a trip, new gear, or a class you’d actually attend. unused choices still cost you.",
      "title": "That Unused Gym Membership"
    },
    {
      "text": "Saying yes to too many projects boosts your reputation but drains time you could spend resting or focusing deeply. Overcommitment is basically opportunity cost in disguise.",
      "title": "Overbooking Your Schedule"
    },
    {
      "text": "Buying a discounted gadget because it’s on sale trades away cash for something you didn’t really want. The deal feels good, but it might cost you the ability to buy what you truly value later.",
      "title": "Chasing a “Good Deal”"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Sabe quando você marca um ‘check’ na lista de tarefas e sente aquele mini alívio? Esse momentinho gostoso é o cérebro liberando dopamina por completar algo — mesmo que seja só lavar a louça.",
      "title": "Checklist do dia"
    },
    {
      "text": "No trabalho, aquele impulso de continuar um projeto porque você teve um pequeno avanço vem desse empurrão interno. Cada progresso vira um sinal de que “vale a pena continuar”, e isso te puxa pra frente.",
      "title": "Avanços que empurram"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ao rolar o feed e encontrar um vídeo perfeito “do nada”, seu cérebro ganha uma faísca de dopamina. É esse acerto imprevisível que faz você continuar rolando sem perceber o tempo passar.",
      "title": "Feed infinito"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando você abre um pacote de comida que adora, só o cheiro já te deixa animado. Não é o sabor em si — é o cérebro antecipando o prazer e te preparando para aproveitar.",
      "title": "Cheiro que anima"
    },
    {
      "text": "Se você gosta de games, aquela sensação de “só mais uma fase” não é só diversão. Cada objetivo cumprido dá ao cérebro pequenas recompensas que te mantêm engajado.",
      "title": "Mais uma fase"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando você recebe uma mensagem de alguém importante, aquele vibrar do celular dispara uma expectativa. Às vezes a dopamina vem da curiosidade sobre o que está por vir, não da conversa em si.",
      "title": "Notificação inesperada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Na academia, completar uma série difícil pode trazer uma sensação de triunfo que dá vontade de continuar. Pequenas vitórias físicas acionam esse mesmo sistema de recompensa.",
      "title": "Vitória no treino"
    },
    {
      "text": "Planejar uma viagem e imaginar o que vai viver já dá um entusiasmo bom. A dopamina aparece na própria antecipação, nutrindo o desejo de seguir organizando tudo.",
      "title": "Planejando a viagem"
    }
  ]
}
